.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Chetwynd","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Chatwin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Chatwin","meanings":["English (Warwickshire and Staffordshire): habitational name from a place in Shropshire called Chetwynd, from the Old English personal name <i>Ceatta</i> + Old English <i>(ge)wind</i> ‘winding ascent’."]}]},{"name":"Philip","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Greek name <i>Philippos</i>, meaning ‘lover of horses’, from <i>philein</i> ‘to love’ + <i>hippos</i> ‘horse’. This was popular in the classical period and since. It was the name of the father of  Alexander the Great . It was also the name of one of Christ's apostles, of a deacon ordained by the apostles after the death of Christ, and of several other early saints.  See also  Philippa ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705190,"age":25,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Philip De Chetwynd was born in 1265, in Ingestre, Staffordshire, England, his father, Sir PHILLIP Chetwynd Lord of Igesture, was 25 and his mother, ISABELLA Mutton (Motton) (Mittin) ,heiress, was 25. He married Isabella Puleston in 1294, in Ingestre, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 3 sons and 1 daughter. He died in 1306, at the age of 41."},"et":{"1265–1306":"1265–1306","–Male":"Surnud","1280–1350":"1280–1350","1294–1352":"1294–1352","1295–1346":"1295–1346","